'''Tsubaichi''' (海柘榴市) was an ancient [[Market (place)|marketplace]] located in [[Yamato Province]], Japan. Over time, it became a [[Shukuba|post station]] from the [[Heian period]]. It is also referred to as '''Usubuichi''', '''Tsubakiichi''', and '''Tunakiichi''', with its name evolving from "Tsubakiichi" to "Tsubaiichi." It is believed to have been situated in the present-day Kanaya area of {{ill|Sakurai, Nara|ja|桜井市}}, though some theories suggest it may have relocated over time.{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|11=728–729}}{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}}
The area was a major transportation hub from the [[Asuka period]], intersecting the [[Hase River (Nara)|Hase River]], Teragawa waterways, and major roads like the {{ill|Yoko Ōji (Nara)|ja|横大路 (奈良県)}}, {{ill|Hase Kaidō|ja|初瀬街道}}, and {{ill|Ise Kaidō|ja|伊勢街道}} running east-west, as well as {{ill|Uetsu Michi|ja|上街道 (上ツ道)}}, {{ill|Abe Yamada Michi|ja|安倍山田道}}, and {{ill|Yamanobe no Michi|ja|山辺の道}} running north-south.{{sfn|Sakurai City History Compilation Committee|1979|11=75–77}}{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|11=728–729}}{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} Tsubaichi served as a gateway to capitals like {{ill|Oshikuma Palace|ja|小墾田宮}}, hosted {{ill|Ekiya|ja|駅家}}, and was a place for punishments and {{ill|Utagaki|ja|歌垣}} gatherings.{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|11=728–729}}{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}}
After the capital moved to {{ill|Heian-kyō|ja|平安京}}, Tsubaichi flourished as a post station for {{ill|Hase-dera (Nara)|ja|長谷寺}} pilgrims.{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} It a11ears in works like ''{{ill|The Pillow Book|ja|枕草子}}'', diaries of Heian nobility, and ''{{ill|The Tale of Genji|ja|源氏物語}}''.{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|11=728–729}}
== Location and "Yaso no Chimata" == [[File:海柘榴市の所在地.png|thumb|450px|Location of Tsubaichi and major Asuka-period facilities]] Tsubaichi is believed to have been located near present-day Kanaya, on the right bank of the {{ill|Hase River (Nara)|ja|初瀬川 (奈良県)}} in Sakurai City.{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} This area hosts the Tsubaichi Kannon-dō, whose main statues date to the {{ill|Genki (era)|ja|元亀}} era.{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} However, some theories suggest Tsubaichi moved here after the Heian period, citing the area's unsuitability as a hub ("chimata").{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|11=728–729}}{{sfn|Watari|2008|11=169–172}}
== Market and Origins == Tsubaichi was a significant market alongside {{ill|Karuichi|ja|軽市}}, Ato Kusaichi, and Ekaiichi during the Asuka period.{{sfn|Watanabe|1980|11=22–32}} While its founding period is uncertain, it may date between the 2nd and 5th centuries.{{sfn|Higuchi|1958|11=90–94}}
== Utagaki == Tsubaichi was a location for {{ill|Utagaki|ja|歌垣}}, a traditional courtship ritual. It first a11ears in the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}}'' account of Emperor {{ill|Buretsu|ja|武烈天皇}}, detailing a romantic exchange between the prince and a local maiden.{{sfn|Watanabe|1980|11=1–7}}{{sfn|Satō|1974|11=58–61}}
== Tsubaichi as a Post Station == During the Heian period, Tsubaichi thrived as a stop for {{ill|Hase-dera (Nara)|ja|長谷寺}} pilgrims. ''The Pillow Book'' praises its lively atmosphere.{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} In {{ill|The Tale of Genji|ja|源氏物語}}, it serves as a meeting place for characters on pilgrimage.{{sfn|Sakurai City History Compilation Committee|1979b|11=792–793}}
== Decline == By the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代}}, post station activity shifted to {{ill|Miwa City|ja|三輪市}}.{{sfn|Sakurai City History Compilation Committee|1979|11=183–185}}
