[[en:Tsubaki Market]]
{{DEFAULTSORT:Tsubaki Market}}

'''Tsubaichi''' (海柘榴市) was an ancient [[Market (place)|marketplace]] located in [[Yamato Province]], Japan. Over time, it became a [[Shukuba|post station]] from the [[Heian period]]. It is also referred to as '''Usubuichi''', '''Tsubakiichi''', and '''Tunakiichi''', with its name evolving from "Tsubakiichi" to "Tsubaiichi." It is believed to have been situated in the present-day Kanaya area of {{ill|Sakurai, Nara|ja|桜井市|12=draft|12=draft}}, though some theories suggest it may have relocated over time.{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|pp=728–729}}{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}}

The area was a major transportation hub from the [[Asuka period]], intersecting the [[Hase River (Nara)|Hase River]], Teragawa waterways, and major roads like the {{ill|Yoko Ōji (Nara)|ja|横大路 (奈良県)|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hase Kaidō|ja|初瀬街道|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Ise Kaidō|ja|伊勢街道|12=draft|12=draft}} running east-west, as well as {{ill|Uetsu Michi|ja|上街道 (上ツ道)|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Abe Yamada Michi|ja|安倍山田道|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Yamanobe no Michi|ja|山辺の道|12=draft|12=draft}} running north-south.{{sfn|Sakurai City History Compilation Committee|1979|pp=75–77}}{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|pp=728–729}}{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} Tsubaichi served as a gateway to capitals like {{ill|Oshikuma Palace|ja|小墾田宮|12=draft|12=draft}}, hosted {{ill|Ekiya|ja|駅家|12=draft|12=draft}}, and was a place for punishments and {{ill|Utagaki|ja|歌垣|12=draft|12=draft}} gatherings.{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|pp=728–729}}{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}}

After the capital moved to {{ill|Heian-kyō|ja|平安京|12=draft|12=draft}}, Tsubaichi flourished as a post station for {{ill|Hase-dera (Nara)|ja|長谷寺|12=draft|12=draft}} pilgrims.{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} It appears in works like ''{{ill|The Pillow Book|ja|枕草子|12=draft|12=draft}}'', diaries of Heian nobility, and ''{{ill|The Tale of Genji|ja|源氏物語|12=draft|12=draft}}''.{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|pp=728–729}}

== Location and "Yaso no Chimata" ==
[[File:海柘榴市の所在地.png|thumb|450px|Location of Tsubaichi and major Asuka-period facilities]]
Tsubaichi is believed to have been located near present-day Kanaya, on the right bank of the {{ill|Hase River (Nara)|ja|初瀬川 (奈良県)|12=draft|12=draft}} in Sakurai City.{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} This area hosts the Tsubaichi Kannon-dō, whose main statues date to the {{ill|Genki (era)|ja|元亀|12=draft|12=draft}} era.{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} However, some theories suggest Tsubaichi moved here after the Heian period, citing the area's unsuitability as a hub ("chimata").{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|pp=728–729}}{{sfn|Watari|2008|pp=169–172}}

== Market and Origins ==
Tsubaichi was a significant market alongside {{ill|Karuichi|ja|軽市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Ato Kusaichi, and Ekaiichi during the Asuka period.{{sfn|Watanabe|1980|pp=22–32}} While its founding period is uncertain, it may date between the 2nd and 5th centuries.{{sfn|Higuchi|1958|pp=90–94}}

== Utagaki ==
Tsubaichi was a location for {{ill|Utagaki|ja|歌垣|12=draft|12=draft}}, a traditional courtship ritual. It first appears in the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}'' account of Emperor {{ill|Buretsu|ja|武烈天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}, detailing a romantic exchange between the prince and a local maiden.{{sfn|Watanabe|1980|pp=1–7}}{{sfn|Satō|1974|pp=58–61}}

== Tsubaichi as a Post Station ==
During the Heian period, Tsubaichi thrived as a stop for {{ill|Hase-dera (Nara)|ja|長谷寺|12=draft|12=draft}} pilgrims. ''The Pillow Book'' praises its lively atmosphere.{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} In {{ill|The Tale of Genji|ja|源氏物語|12=draft|12=draft}}, it serves as a meeting place for characters on pilgrimage.{{sfn|Sakurai City History Compilation Committee|1979b|pp=792–793}}

== Decline ==
By the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, post station activity shifted to {{ill|Miwa City|ja|三輪市|12=draft|12=draft}}.{{sfn|Sakurai City History Compilation Committee|1979|pp=183–185}}

