[[File:海柘榴市の所在地.png|thumb|450px|Location of Tsubaichi and major Asuka-period facilities]]
Tsubaichi is believed to have been located near present-day Kanaya, on the right bank of the {{ill|Hase River (Nara)|ja|初瀬川 (奈良県)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hase River (Nara)|qq=}} in Sakurai City.{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} This area hosts the Tsubaichi Kannon-dō, whose main statues date to the [[:en:Genki (era)|Genki (era)]] era.{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} However, some theories suggest Tsubaichi moved here after the Heian period, citing the area's unsuitability as a hub ("chimata").{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|pp=728–729}}{{sfn|Watari|2008|pp=169–172}}

== Market and Origins ==
Tsubaichi was a significant market alongside {{ill|Karuichi|ja|軽市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Karuichi|qq=}}, Ato Kusaichi, and Ekaiichi during the Asuka period.{{sfn|Watanabe|1980|pp=22–32}} While its founding period is uncertain, it may date between the 2nd and 5th centuries.{{sfn|Higuchi|1958|pp=90–94}}

== Utagaki ==
Tsubaichi was a location for [[:en:Utagaki|Utagaki]], a traditional courtship ritual. It first appears in the ''[[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]]'' account of Emperor [[:en:Emperor Buretsu|Buretsu]], detailing a romantic exchange between the prince and a local maiden.{{sfn|Watanabe|1980|pp=1–7}}{{sfn|Satō|1974|pp=58–61}}

== Tsubaichi as a Post Station ==
During the Heian period, Tsubaichi thrived as a stop for [[:en:Hase-dera|Hase-dera (Nara)]] pilgrims. ''The Pillow Book'' praises its lively atmosphere.{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} In [[:en:The Tale of Genji|The Tale of Genji]], it serves as a meeting place for characters on pilgrimage.{{sfn|Sakurai City History Compilation Committee|1979b|pp=792–793}}

== Decline ==
By the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], post station activity shifted to {{ill|Miwa City|ja|三輪市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miwa City|qq=}}.{{sfn|Sakurai City History Compilation Committee|1979|pp=183–185}}

