<!--Tsubaki Market--><!--Tsubaki Market-->

'''Tsubaichi''' (海柘榴市) was an ancient [[Market (place)|marketplace]] located in [[Yamato Province]], Japan. Over time, it became a [[Shukuba|post station]] from the [[Heian period]]. It is also referred to as '''Usubuichi''', '''Tsubakiichi''', and '''Tunakiichi''', with its name evolving from "Tsubakiichi" to "Tsubaiichi." It is believed to have been situated in the present-day Kanaya area of [[:en:Sakurai, Nara|Sakurai, Nara]], though some theories suggest it may have relocated over time.{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|pp=728–729}}{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}}

The area was a major transportation hub from the [[Asuka period]], intersecting the [[Hase River (Nara)|Hase River]], Teragawa waterways, and major roads like the {{ill|Yoko Ōji (Nara)|ja|横大路 (奈良県)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoko Ōji (Nara)|qq=}}, {{ill|Hase Kaidō|ja|初瀬街道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hase Kaidō|qq=}}, and {{ill|Ise Kaidō|ja|伊勢街道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise Kaidō|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 伊勢参宮街道}} running east-west, as well as {{ill|Uetsu Michi|ja|上街道 (上ツ道)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Uetsu Michi|qq=}}, {{ill|Abe Yamada Michi|ja|安倍山田道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Abe Yamada Michi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, and {{ill|Yamanobe-no-Michi|lt=Yamanobe-no-Michi|lt=Yamanobe no Michi|ja|山辺の道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamanobe no Michi|qq=}} running north-south.{{sfn|Sakurai City History Compilation Committee|1979|pp=75–77}}{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|pp=728–729}}{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} Tsubaichi served as a gateway to capitals like {{ill|Oshikuma Palace|ja|小墾田宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oshikuma Palace|qq=}}, hosted {{ill|Ekiya|ja|駅家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ekiya|qq=}}, and was a place for punishments and [[:en:Utagaki|Utagaki]] gatherings.{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|pp=728–729}}{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}}

After the capital moved to [[:en:Heian-kyō|Heian-kyō]], Tsubaichi flourished as a post station for [[:en:Hase-dera|Hase-dera (Nara)]] pilgrims.{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} It appears in works like ''[[:en:The Pillow Book|The Pillow Book]]'', diaries of Heian nobility, and ''[[:en:The Tale of Genji|The Tale of Genji]]''.{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|pp=728–729}}

