'''Tsubaichi''' (海柘榴市) was an ancient [[Market (place)|marketplace]] located in [[Yamato Province]], Japan. Over time, it became a [[Shukuba|post station]] from the [[:en:Heian period|Heian period]]. It is also referred to as '''Usubuichi''', '''Tsubakiichi''', and '''Tunakiichi''', with its name evolving from "Tsubakiichi" to "Tsubaiichi." It is believed to have been situated in the present-day Kanaya area of [[:en:Sakurai, Nara|Sakurai, Nara]], though some theories suggest it may have relocated over time.{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|pp=728–729}}{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}}

The area was a major transportation hub from the [[:en:Asuka period|Asuka period]], intersecting the [[Hase River (Nara)|Hase River]], Teragawa waterways, and major roads like the {{ill|Yoko Ōji (Nara)|ja|横大路 (奈良県)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoko Ōji (Nara)|qq=}}, {{ill|Hase Kaidō|ja|初瀬街道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hase Kaidō|qq=}}, and {{ill|Ise Kaidō|ja|伊勢街道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise Kaidō|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 伊勢参宮街道}} running east-west, as well as {{ill|Uetsu Michi|ja|上街道 (上ツ道)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Uetsu Michi|qq=}}, {{ill|Abe Yamada Michi|ja|安倍山田道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Abe Yamada Michi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, and {{ill|Yamanobe-no-Michi|lt=Yamanobe-no-Michi|lt=Yamanobe no Michi|ja|山辺の道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamanobe no Michi|qq=}} running north-south.{{sfn|Sakurai City History Compilation Committee|1979|pp=75–77}}{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|pp=728–729}}{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} Tsubaichi served as a gateway to capitals like {{ill|Oshikuma Palace|ja|小墾田宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oshikuma Palace|qq=}}, hosted {{ill|Ekiya|ja|駅家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ekiya|qq=}}, and was a place for punishments and [[:en:Utagaki|Utagaki]] gatherings.{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|pp=728–729}}{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}}

After the capital moved to [[:en:Heian-kyō|Heian-kyō]], Tsubaichi flourished as a post station for [[:en:Hase-dera|Hase-dera (Nara)]] pilgrims.{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} It appears in works like ''[[:en:The Pillow Book|The Pillow Book]]'', diaries of Heian nobility, and ''[[:en:The Tale of Genji|The Tale of Genji]]''.{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|pp=728–729}}

== Location and "Yaso no Chimata" ==
[[File:海柘榴市の所在地.png|thumb|450px|Location of Tsubaichi and major Asuka-period facilities]]
Tsubaichi is believed to have been located near present-day Kanaya, on the right bank of the {{ill|Hase River (Nara)|ja|初瀬川 (奈良県)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hase River (Nara)|qq=}} in Sakurai City.{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} This area hosts the Tsubaichi Kannon-dō, whose main statues date to the [[:en:Genki (era)|Genki (era)]] era.{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} However, some theories suggest Tsubaichi moved here after the Heian period, citing the area's unsuitability as a hub ("chimata").{{sfn|Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Compilation Committee|1990|pp=728–729}}{{sfn|Watari|2008|pp=169–172}}

== Market and Origins ==
Tsubaichi was a significant market alongside {{ill|Karuichi|ja|軽市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Karuichi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, Ato Kusaichi, and Ekaiichi during the Asuka period.{{sfn|Watanabe|1980|pp=22–32}} While its founding period is uncertain, it may date between the 2nd and 5th centuries.{{sfn|Higuchi|1958|pp=90–94}}

== Utagaki ==
Tsubaichi was a location for [[:en:Utagaki|Utagaki]], a traditional courtship ritual. It first appears in the ''[[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]]'' account of Emperor [[:en:Emperor Buretsu|Buretsu]], detailing a romantic exchange between the prince and a local maiden.{{sfn|Watanabe|1980|pp=1–7}}{{sfn|Satō|1974|pp=58–61}}

== Tsubaichi as a Post Station ==
During the Heian period, Tsubaichi thrived as a stop for [[:en:Hase-dera|Hase-dera (Nara)]] pilgrims. ''The Pillow Book'' praises its lively atmosphere.{{sfn|Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei|1981|p=430}} In [[:en:The Tale of Genji|The Tale of Genji]], it serves as a meeting place for characters on pilgrimage.{{sfn|Sakurai City History Compilation Committee|1979b|pp=792–793}}

== Decline ==
By the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], post station activity shifted to {{ill|Miwa City|ja|三輪市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miwa City|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}.{{sfn|Sakurai City History Compilation Committee|1979|pp=183–185}}

